+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Wikipedia Gets State Funding in Germany                            |
|   from the we-could-use-some-state-support-too dept.               |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday June 26, @12:22 (The Internet)         |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/26/159232      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]tmk writes "How can Wikipedia be improved? The German government
started a project today to [1]train experts to contribute to Wikipedia.
The goal is to write or improve several hundred articles about renewable
resources in the Internet encyclopedia. The project is funded by the
German Ministry of Nutrition, Agriculture, and Consumer Protection. The
German chapter of the Wikimedia Foundation is hiring a Wikipedian to
coordinate the efforts. 'The challenge will be to motivate experts who
have done good work in other projects to get involved in the community
lexicon. As project director Florian Gerlach told heise online, "Such
expert reports are usually written, edited, and published in the normal
newspapers or even on other websites. But Wikipedia is radically
different: articles there continually grow with input from numerous
authors, who often remain anonymous. The end product is constantly
changing, and third parties can publish their own texts or even change
yours." The future authors will therefore receive some training to help
them work with Wikipedia.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/26/159232

Links:
    0. http://notes.computernotizen.de/
    1. http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/91733


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| IBM's Blue Gene Runs Continuously At 1 Petaflop                    |
|   from the all-i-can-think-is-the-games-you-could-play dept.       |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday June 26, @13:02 (Supercomputing)       |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/26/1517208     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "ZDNet is reporting on IBM's claim that [0]the
Blue Gene/P will continuously operate at more than 1 petaflop. It is
actually capable of 3 quadrillion operations a second, or 3 petaflops.
IBM claims that at 1 petaflop, Blue Gene/P is performing more operations
than a 1.5-mile-high stack of laptops! 'Like the vast majority of other
modern supercomputers, Blue Gene/P is composed of several racks of
servers lashed together in clusters for large computing tasks, such as
running programs that can graphically simulate worldwide weather
patterns. Technologies designed for these computers trickle down into the
mainstream while conventional technologies and components are used to cut
the costs of building these systems. The chip inside Blue Gene/P consists
of four PowerPC 450 cores running at 850MHz each. A 2x2 foot circuit
board containing 32 of the Blue Gene/P chips can churn out 435 billion
operations a second. Thirty two of these boards can be stuffed into a
6-foot-high rack.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/26/1517208

Links:
    0. http://www.zdnet.com.au/news/hardware/soa/IBM-s-Blue-Gene-passes-petaflop-milestone/0,130061702,339279111,00.htm


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Legend of the Syndicate                                            |
|   from the guild-is-life-guild-is-death dept.                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday June 26, @13:46 (Role Playing (Games)) |
|   http://books.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/26/0239237        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

In the world of Massively Multiplayer Online Games, guilds live and die
like generations of fruit flies. In the time it takes you to read this
review, another group of friends will probably have decided to go their
separate ways. Due to what is commonly referred to as 'drama', and the
nature of the currently most popular online game, the modern MMOG guild
tends to be a short-lived affair. A book published about a single guild,
then, has to be discussing a singular organization. And indeed, The
Syndicate has lasted for over a decade. Well known in both Ultima Online
and EverQuest, and going strong into the days of World of Warcraft,
they've had numerous public successes and some notorious failures. Their
tale is a strange, and utterly personal view of the history of Massive
games. It's also highly self-aggrandizing and probably contentious, but
that's to be expected. [0]Legend of the Syndicate is a publication worth
reading by anyone interested in the history of the Massive genre, or the
future of social networks online.

This story continues at:
    http://books.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/26/0239237

Discuss this story at:
    http://books.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/26/0239237

Links:
    0. http://www.avaripress.com/books-authors/legend-of-the-syndicate/


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Wireless Networks Causing Headaches For Businesses                 |
|   from the help-desks-needing-help dept.                           |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday June 26, @14:27 (Wireless Networking|
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/26/1748235     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]ElvaWSJ writes "Wi-Fi was supposed to reduce complications, not create
new ones. But [1]in many offices Wi-Fi has been a headache. Like all
radio signals, Wi-Fi is subject to interference. Its low power — less
than even a typical cellphone — means that walls and cabinets can
significantly reduce signal strength. Wi-Fi also creates networks that
are more open than wired ones, raising security issues. And Wi-Fi has
caused problems for virtual private networks. Some VPNs require a lot of
processing power. If a wireless access point — at home, at the office, or
on the road — isn't robust enough, a user often gets bumped off the
connection."

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/26/1748235

Links:
    0. http://online.wsj.com/public/us
    1. http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB118282236794247982.html?mod=blog


